headline.main: Governor Clark's Address at the Massachusetts State Temperance Convention.

docs.lead_paragraph: Gov. CLARK, of New-York, was introduced, and, although in feeble health, addressed the Convention as follows: MR. PRESIDENT: It was not my purpose in coming here to undertake to entertain you with a speech. My efforts and labors in the Temperance cause have been in other departments than speech-making.

docs.lead_paragraph: By the arrival at this port of the Hermann, from Southampton, on the 25th, and the Asia at Boston, from Liverpool, on the 23th ult., we have received the details of five days' later news from Europe.

headline.main: SENATOR BROOKS VS. ARCHBISHOP HUGHES.; The "Sinking Condition of our Country"--The Property in Calvary Cemetery, &c. PARTICULARS AS TO CALVARY CEMETERY.

docs.lead_paragraph: To the Editor of the New-York Daily Times: The following are the texts of the Archbishop's "Card to the Public:" "Unfortunately the moral attributes of our progressive greatness are, in the estimation of the civilized nations of the world, sinking from day to day." "Whether we like it or not, our course in the esteem of the civilized world has at this moment a rather downward tendency."

docs.lead_paragraph: GEORGE P. SCARBURGH, Esq., principal Professor of William and Mary's College, Virginia, has been appointed Judge of the Court of Claims, vice LUMPKIN, Declined. The appointee has always eschewed politics.
